RESEARCH
Evidence-based methods for learning a foreign language, with a focus on
consolidating new vocabulary in long-term memory.

Compiled 2026-07-24. Every claim below is tied to a numbered reference in the
REFERENCES section; numbers in brackets, e.g. [1], point there.


====================================================================
1. THE HEADLINE FINDING: RETRIEVAL, NOT RE-READING
====================================================================

Trying to recall a word from memory is what consolidates it. Re-reading or
re-studying it does almost nothing once you already "know" it.

* Karpicke & Roediger (2008) [1] taught 40 Swahili-English pairs (mashua -
  boat) under four schedules. Once a word had been recalled correctly, it was
  either (a) still studied and still tested, (b) still studied but dropped from
  testing, (c) dropped from study but still tested, or (d) dropped from both.
  One week later, dropping the STUDY made no difference; dropping the TESTING
  was devastating. Recall after a week was roughly 80% for the conditions that
  kept testing, and roughly 35% for those that dropped it.
  Practical reading: once you can produce a word, keep quizzing it and stop
  re-reading it.

* The same study found learners were badly calibrated: they predicted all four
  conditions would come out about equal. Subjective ease is not a reliable
  signal of learning [1].

* Rowland's (2014) meta-analysis [2] of the testing effect across 159
  experiments confirms the general benefit (g = 0.50) and shows the size
  depends on effort: initial tests requiring free/cued RECALL beat recognition
  (multiple choice), and feedback after the attempt enlarges the effect.
  Practical reading: prefer "produce the word" over "pick it from four
  options", and always show the answer afterwards.

* Nakata (2016) [3] applied this specifically to L2 vocabulary and compared
  retrieval formats directly. Recall formats outperformed recognition formats,
  and the L2-to-L1 vs L1-to-L2 direction matters for what kind of knowledge you
  end up with: retrieving the MEANING trains comprehension, retrieving the FORM
  trains production. They are not interchangeable.


====================================================================
2. SPACING: WHEN TO COME BACK TO A WORD
====================================================================

* Cepeda, Pashler, Vul, Wixted & Rohrer (2006) [4] synthesised 839 assessments
  from 317 experiments. Spaced study beats massed study essentially everywhere
  in verbal recall. The key nuance: the optimal gap between sessions is not
  fixed - it grows with how long you need to remember the material.

* Cepeda, Vul, Rohrer, Wixted & Pashler (2008) [5] quantified that with 1,354
  participants, gaps up to 3.5 months and final tests up to 1 year out. As a
  proportion of the retention interval, the optimal gap SHRINKS as the horizon
  lengthens: ~20-40% of a 1-week horizon, but only ~5-10% of a 1-year horizon.
  Practical reading (rules of thumb from their ridgeline):
    - want it in 1 week   -> review after ~1-2 days
    - want it in 1 month  -> review after ~1 week
    - want it in 1 year   -> review after ~3-4 weeks
  There is no single "correct" interval; there is a correct interval FOR A
  GIVEN TARGET DATE. Over-long gaps cost far less than over-short ones - the
  curve falls off gently on the right, steeply on the left.

* Expanding vs equal intervals. The popular claim that intervals must expand
  (1d, 3d, 7d, 21d...) is weakly supported. Nakata (2015) [6] ran the cleanest
  L2 test - 128 Japanese university students, 20 English-Japanese pairs,
  crossing schedule type (expanding vs equal) with amount of spacing (massed /
  short / medium / long). Expanding spacing won, but the advantage was small
  and conditional; the AMOUNT of spacing mattered far more than its SHAPE.
  Practical reading: getting any real spacing in is what counts. Don't
  over-engineer the curve.

* Spacing survives outside the lab. Nakata, Tada, McLean & Kim (2021) [7] ran
  distributed retrieval across a whole university semester: cumulative tests
  (each test re-covering earlier words) beat one-shot tests on delayed
  post-tests. Practical reading: never retire a word permanently from the
  quiz pool.


====================================================================
3. DELIBERATE STUDY VS PICKING WORDS UP FROM CONTEXT
====================================================================

Both work. They work at very different rates, and they build different things.

* Incidental learning (reading, listening, watching) is real but slow. Webb,
  Uchihara & Yanagisawa (2023) [8] meta-analysed 24 studies (N = 2,771): only
  9-18% of target words were learned on immediate post-tests and 6-17% on
  delayed ones, with reading (17%/15%), listening (15%/13%) and
  reading-while-listening (13%/17%) roughly comparable.

* Intentional, word-focused study is several times more efficient. Webb,
  Yanagisawa & Uchihara (2020) [9] meta-analysed 100 effect sizes from 22
  studies of flashcards, word lists, writing and fill-in-the-blanks: 60.1%
  (meaning-recall) and 58.5% (form-recall) learned immediately. Note the decay,
  though: 39.4% and 25.1% respectively on DELAYED tests. Deliberate study gets
  words in fast; only spaced retrieval keeps them there.

* Repetition drives the incidental route. Uchihara, Webb & Yanagisawa (2019)
  [10] found a medium correlation (r = 0.34) between number of encounters and
  learning across 45 effect sizes (N = 1,918). More exposures help, but the
  return per exposure is modest - which is why extensive reading alone is a
  slow way to build a lexicon.

* Deliberate study is not "shallow". A common objection is that flashcard
  learning yields inert knowledge. Elgort (2011) [11] tested this with masked
  repetition priming, form priming and automatic semantic priming on 48
  deliberately learned pseudowords: the learned items showed a prime lexicality
  effect and automatic semantic priming, i.e. they had genuinely been
  integrated into the mental lexicon, not merely memorised as pairs.

* Practical synthesis: use deliberate study to acquire form-meaning links
  quickly, and extensive input to deepen, contextualise and refresh them.


====================================================================
4. HOW HARD YOU PROCESS A WORD
====================================================================

* Involvement Load Hypothesis - Laufer & Hulstijn (2001) [12]. Retention scales
  with a task's involvement load, made of three components:
    NEED       - do you actually need the word to finish the task?
    SEARCH     - do you have to look up form or meaning yourself?
    EVALUATION - do you have to compare the word against alternatives, or
                 judge whether it fits this specific context?
  Their experiment compared reading comprehension, reading + fill-in-the-gap,
  and composition-writing using the target words. Retention was highest for
  composition, lower for fill-in, lowest for plain reading.
  Practical reading: WRITING YOUR OWN SENTENCE with a new word beats filling a
  gap, which beats merely meeting the word in text.

* Mnemonic keyword method - Atkinson & Raugh (1975) [13]. Two stages: link the
  foreign word to an L1 word that sounds like part of it (the keyword), then
  form a vivid mental image of the keyword interacting with the translation.
  With 120 Russian words, keyword learners outscored controls substantially,
  and the advantage was still there at a 6-week delay.
  Practical reading: most valuable for stubborn, arbitrary, non-cognate words.
  It is a fast way IN; retrieval practice is still what keeps it.


====================================================================
5. SLEEP: THE PART YOU DO NOT DO CONSCIOUSLY
====================================================================

Consolidation of new words is not finished when the study session is. Newly
learned words start as isolated hippocampal traces and only become part of the
lexicon - competing with similar-sounding known words during recognition -
after offline consolidation, mostly during sleep.

* Tamminen, Payne, Stickgold, Wamsley & Gaskell (2010) [14] showed that the
  emergence of lexical competition for novel words was linked to sleep spindle
  activity, a marker of hippocampal-neocortical dialogue, while slow-wave sleep
  duration correlated with better recognition memory.

* Schimke, Angwin, Cheng & Copland (2021) [15] meta-analysed 25 studies (29
  between-group comparisons, 1,396 participants): sleep beat equivalent
  wakefulness overall (g = 0.50), with g = 0.57 for recall and g = 0.52 for
  recognition. The effect on lexical-integration measures was smaller.

Practical reading: study new words in the evening rather than cramming them
the morning of a test, protect sleep during intensive study periods, and
expect a word to feel more "settled" the next day than it did at encoding.


====================================================================
6. SESSION DESIGN DETAILS
====================================================================

* Set size. Nakata & Webb (2016) [16] compared "part" learning (small sets
  studied to criterion) with "whole" learning (one large set cycled through).
  Larger sets, which necessarily space each item further apart, produced better
  delayed retention despite feeling harder during the session. Practical
  reading: resist the urge to drill a small batch until it feels solid.

* Difficulty should be desirable, not crushing. Across [1], [2] and [6] the
  pattern is consistent: conditions that feel harder in the moment (longer
  gaps, recall instead of recognition, bigger sets) produce worse in-session
  performance and better long-term retention. Judge a method by delayed
  recall, never by how fluent the session felt.

* Feedback. [2] and [3] both find retrieval works best when the correct answer
  is shown after the attempt - including after a failed attempt. A failed
  retrieval followed by feedback is a productive event, not a wasted one.


====================================================================
7. A PROTOCOL THAT FOLLOWS FROM THE ABOVE
====================================================================

1. Choose target words by frequency/usefulness, then learn them deliberately
   (paired-associate study or flashcards) - it is the fast route in [9].
2. Use a hard keyword image for words that resist learning [13].
3. Switch to retrieval the moment you can recall the word once. Stop
   re-reading it [1].
4. Use recall, not multiple choice, and alternate directions: L2->meaning for
   comprehension, meaning->L2 for production [3].
5. Always reveal the answer after the attempt, right or wrong [2].
6. Space reviews at roughly 5-10% of your target retention horizon; err long
   rather than short [4][5]. Any reasonable expanding schedule is fine [6].
7. Keep already-learned words in the rotation - cumulative, never retired [7].
8. Write your own sentence with each new word at least once [12].
9. Read and listen extensively alongside, for depth and refresh [8][10].
10. Sleep on it; put new material in an evening session [14][15].


